o eradicate sign language. "Baynton's brilliant and detailed history, Forbidden Signs, reminds us that debates over the use of dialects or languages are really the linguistic tip of a mostly submerged argument about power, social control, nationalism, who has the right to speak and who has the right to control modes of speech."—Lennard J. Davis, The Nation "Forbidden Signs is replete with good things."—Hugh Kenner, New York Times Book Review  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDeafxMeans of communicationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDeafzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aLanguage and languages. 0aSign languagevStudy and teachingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial sciences. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aamerican culture, usa, united states of america, sign language, alexander graham bell, deaf, deafness, disability, disabled population, 19th century, debate, civilization, civilized, power, social control, nationalism, speech, communication, history, historical, race, gender, identity, nature, normality, paternalism, mutism, community.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226039688423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226039688/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles